This next patient is interesting.

60
00:14:32,600 --> 00:14:35,058
I've been following the case for years.

61
00:14:35,270 --> 00:14:37,262
A 29-year-old female,

62
00:14:39,691 --> 00:14:42,229
diagnosed as acute schizo-affective disorder.

63
00:14:42,443 --> 00:14:44,480
The usual indicators: depression, anxiety,

64
00:14:44,696 --> 00:14:47,234
violent acting out, delusions of persecution.

65
00:14:53,913 --> 00:14:57,031
The delusional architecture is fairly unique.

66
00:14:57,250 --> 00:15:00,084
She believes that a machine
called the Terminator,

67
00:15:00,295 --> 00:15:04,296
which looked human, of course,
was sent back through time to kill her.

68
00:15:04,507 --> 00:15:05,623
That's original.

69
00:15:05,842 --> 00:15:08,550
And also, that the father of her child

70
00:15:08,761 --> 00:15:11,595
was a soldier sent back to protect her.

71
00:15:11,806 --> 00:15:14,093
- No?
- He was from the future too.

72
00:15:14,309 --> 00:15:19,100
The year 2029, if I remember correctly.

73
00:15:19,314 --> 00:15:21,180
And here we are.

74
00:15:22,025 --> 00:15:23,061
Morning, Sarah.

75
00:15:27,530 --> 00:15:31,365
Good morning, Dr Silberman. How's the knee?

76
00:15:33,286 --> 00:15:35,152
Fine, Sarah.

77
00:15:36,372 --> 00:15:41,538
She, er... stabbed me in the kneecap
with my pen a few weeks ago.

78
00:15:42,378 --> 00:15:43,710
Repeated escape attempts...

79
00:15:54,057 --> 00:15:56,140
Let's move on, shall we?

80
00:15:56,351 --> 00:15:59,976
Lewis, I don't like to see the patients
disrupting their rooms like this.

81
00:16:00,188 --> 00:16:03,272
- See she takes her Thorazine.
- Sure. I'll take care of it.

82
00:16:26,839 --> 00:16:28,831
Are you the legal guardian of John Connor?

83
00:16:29,592 --> 00:16:31,959
That's right, Officer. What's he done now?

84
00:16:32,804 --> 00:16:35,512
- Could I speak with him, please?
- You could if he were here.

85
00:16:35,723 --> 00:16:38,431
He took off on his bike this morning
so he could be anywhere.

86
00:16:38,643 --> 00:16:42,136
- Do you have a photograph of John?
- Yeah. Hold on.

87
00:16:45,108 --> 00:16:47,441
You gonna tell me what this is about?

88
00:16:47,652 --> 00:16:49,518
I just need to ask him a few questions.

89
00:16:51,990 --> 00:16:54,983
He's a good-looking boy.
Do you mind if I keep this picture?

90
00:16:55,201 --> 00:16:58,444
No, go on. There was a guy here
this morning looking for him, too.

91
00:16:58,663 --> 00:17:00,370
Yeah, a big guy on a bike.

92
00:17:00,581 --> 00:17:02,493
Has that got something to do with this?

93
00:17:04,919 --> 00:17:08,754
No. I wouldn't worry about him.

94
00:17:10,091 --> 00:17:12,674
Thanks for your cooperation.

95
00:17:13,928 --> 00:17:16,420
Please insert your stolen card now.

96
00:17:24,105 --> 00:17:25,687
PIN number.

97
00:17:27,066 --> 00:17:30,101
- Hurry up. This is taking too long.
- Go, baby. Go, baby.

98
00:17:31,821 --> 00:17:33,153
All right!

99
00:17:33,364 --> 00:17:36,857
- PIN number 9003.
- Where'd you learn this stuff from?

100
00:17:37,076 --> 00:17:39,489
From my mom. My real mom, I mean.

101
00:17:40,663 --> 00:17:43,781
Withdraw three-zero-zero bucks.

102
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,708
Come on, baby. Come on! Come on!

103
00:17:46,919 --> 00:17:49,002
- Yes!
- Hey, it worked.

104
00:17:49,213 --> 00:17:52,752
All right. Easy money. Come on!

105
00:17:55,386 --> 00:17:57,378
Yes! Piece of cake.

106
00:18:02,977 --> 00:18:05,765
- Is that her?
- Yes.

107
00:18:05,980 --> 00:18:10,020
- She's pretty cool, huh?
- No, she's a complete psycho.

108
00:18:10,234 --> 00:18:13,853
That's why she's at Pescadero.
It's a mental institute, okay?

109
00:18:14,739 --> 00:18:18,110
She tried to blow up a computer factory,
but she got shot and arrested.

110
00:18:18,326 --> 00:18:19,783
No shit.

111
00:18:20,620 --> 00:18:22,907
She's a total loser.

112
00:18:23,122 --> 00:18:25,705
Come on. Let's go spend some money.

113
00:18:41,265 --> 00:18:44,804
It's like a giant strobe light

114
00:18:45,019 --> 00:18:47,261
burning right through my eyes.

115
00:18:51,484 --> 00:18:53,726
Somehow, I can still see.

116
00:18:59,784 --> 00:19:01,571
Oh, God.

117
00:19:05,248 --> 00:19:08,332
We know the dream's the same every night.

118
00:19:08,709 --> 00:19:11,873
- Why do I have to...
- Please continue.

119
00:19:15,800 --> 00:19:18,292
Children look like burnt paper.

120
00:19:20,054 --> 00:19:21,511
Black.

121
00:19:22,473 --> 00:19:24,089
Not moving.

122
00:19:26,018 --> 00:19:28,852
And then the blast wave hits them.

123
00:19:37,822 --> 00:19:40,235
And they fly apart like leaves.

124
00:19:42,201 --> 00:19:47,367
Dreams of cataclysm,
the end of the world are very common.

125
00:19:49,375 --> 00:19:53,460
It's not a dream, you moron. It's real.

126
00:19:53,671 --> 00:19:57,415
- I know the date it happens.
- I'm sure it feels very real to you.

127
00:19:57,633 --> 00:20:02,719
On August 29, 1997, it's gonna feel
pretty fuckin' real to you, too!

128
00:20:04,015 --> 00:20:06,382
Anybody not wearing two-million sunblock

129
00:20:06,601 --> 00:20:09,093
is gonna have a real bad day. Get it?

130
00:20:09,604 --> 00:20:12,312
God! You think you're safe and alive.

131
00:20:12,523 --> 00:20:14,685
You're already dead. Everybody!

132
00:20:14,901 --> 00:20:17,314
Him. You. You're dead already.

133
00:20:17,528 --> 00:20:20,271
This whole place, everything you see is gone!

134
00:20:20,489 --> 00:20:23,448
You're the one
living in a fucking dream, Silberman!

135
00:20:23,659 --> 00:20:26,242
Cos I know it happened! It happened!

136
00:20:37,548 --> 00:20:39,460
I feel much better now.

137
00:20:40,676 --> 00:20:42,417
Clearer.

138
00:20:42,637 --> 00:20:47,974
Yes, your attitude has been
much improved lately.

139
00:20:57,193 --> 00:20:59,526
It's helped me to have a goal,

140
00:21:00,321 --> 00:21:02,779
something to look forward to.

141
00:21:02,990 --> 00:21:04,026
What is that?

142
00:21:04,909 --> 00:21:10,371
Well, you said that if I showed
improvement after six months,

143
00:21:10,581 --> 00:21:13,119
you would transfer me
to the minimum security wing

144
00:21:13,334 --> 00:21:16,418
and I could have visitors.

145
00:21:17,713 --> 00:21:21,002
Well, it's been six months and...

146
00:21:22,927 --> 00:21:25,044
I was looking forward to seeing my son.

147
00:21:26,264 --> 00:21:27,755
I see.

148
00:21:30,935 --> 00:21:36,021
Let's go back to what you were saying
about those Terminator machines.

149
00:21:36,232 --> 00:21:39,475
Now you think they don't exist?

150
00:21:39,694 --> 00:21:41,902
They don't exist.

151
00:21:42,113 --> 00:21:43,695
I know that now.

152
00:21:43,906 --> 00:21:45,693
But you've told me on many occasions

153
00:21:45,908 --> 00:21:49,242
about how you crushed one
in a hydraulic press.

154
00:21:50,621 --> 00:21:53,614
If I had, there would have been
some evidence.

155
00:21:53,833 --> 00:21:56,120
They would have found something
at the factory.

156
00:21:56,335 --> 00:21:58,327
I see.

157
00:21:58,546 --> 00:22:02,381
So, you don't believe any more
that the company covered it up?

158
00:22:04,552 --> 00:22:07,010
No. Why would they?

159
00:22:07,930 --> 00:22:10,172
Let's try a new position right there.

160
00:22:10,391 --> 00:22:14,556
The neuronal sensors are correct,
because it works.

161
00:22:14,770 --> 00:22:17,262
- Right.
- Those neurons are all centred.

162
00:22:18,149 --> 00:22:20,141
Maybe the inhibitor circuits failed...

163
00:22:20,359 --> 00:22:21,440
Mr Dyson?

164
00:22:22,278 --> 00:22:25,316
Mr Dyson, the materials team
is running another...

165
00:22:26,490 --> 00:22:28,026
- Mr Dyson.
- Yes?

166
00:22:28,242 --> 00:22:31,076
The materials team is running
another series this afternoon.

167
00:22:31,287 --> 00:22:34,121
You have to sign for the... Er... it.

168
00:22:34,332 --> 00:22:37,245
- You have to sign it out.
- Okay. Come on. I'll get it.

169
00:22:39,045 --> 00:22:40,081
Mr Dyson,

170
00:22:40,296 --> 00:22:42,128
I know I haven't been here long, but
I was wondering if you could tell me,

171
00:22:42,340 --> 00:22:44,502
- I mean, if you know...
- Know what?

172
00:22:44,717 --> 00:22:47,255
Well, if you know where "it" came from.

173
00:22:47,470 --> 00:22:50,759
I asked them that very same question
once. You know what they told me?

174
00:22:50,973 --> 00:22:52,134
"Don't ask."

175
00:22:58,856 --> 00:23:00,939
- Good morning, Mr Dyson.
- How's it going?

176
00:23:01,942 --> 00:23:03,228
Insert key.

177
00:23:03,444 --> 00:23:06,403
Left on three, two, one, turn.

178
00:23:10,326 --> 00:23:12,067
- How are the wife and kids?
- Great. Thanks.

179
00:23:12,286 --> 00:23:13,447
There you go.

180
00:23:41,273 --> 00:23:43,731
So, what do you think, Doctor?

181
00:23:44,819 --> 00:23:46,560
I have shown improvement, haven't I?

182
00:23:47,947 --> 00:23:50,985
Well, Sarah, here's the problem.

183
00:23:51,909 --> 00:23:53,525
I know how smart you are.

184
00:23:54,286 --> 00:23:56,243
I think you're just telling me
what I want to hear.

185
00:23:57,498 --> 00:24:00,081
I don't think you really believe
what you're telling me today.

186
00:24:00,376 --> 00:24:04,286
I think if I put you in minimum security,
you'll just try to escape again.

187
00:24:09,385 --> 00:24:11,968
You have to let me see my son.

188
00:24:12,930 --> 00:24:14,421
Please.

189
00:24:15,933 --> 00:24:17,219
Please.

190
00:24:18,519 --> 00:24:22,388
He's in great danger. He's naked without me.

191
00:24:22,606 --> 00:24:24,347
If I could just make a phone call...

192
00:24:24,567 --> 00:24:27,480
Afraid not. Not for a while.

193
00:24:29,363 --> 00:24:31,696
I don't see any choice
but to recommend to the review board

194
00:24:31,907 --> 00:24:34,194
that you stay here for another six months.

195
00:24:37,538 --> 00:24:39,779
I'll kill you, you son of a bitch!

196
00:24:41,876 --> 00:24:45,119
- Get her off of me!
- You son of a bitch!

197
00:24:45,337 --> 00:24:47,579
10cc of sodium amobarbital, stat!

198
00:24:49,258 --> 00:24:51,875
- You don't know what you're doing!
- Get some restraints in here now!

199
00:24:54,638 --> 00:24:57,255
You don't know what you're doing!

200
00:25:01,687 --> 00:25:03,724
Model citizen.

201
00:25:43,103 --> 00:25:45,686
You just missed him.
He was here 15 minutes ago.

202
00:25:45,898 --> 00:25:47,480
He said he was going to the galleria?

203
00:25:47,691 --> 00:25:48,727
Yeah.

204
00:25:48,943 --> 00:25:50,559
The galleria?

205
00:26:36,615 --> 00:26:38,982
I'm gonna get some quarters.
I'll be back, all right?

206
00:26:54,049 --> 00:26:56,666
- Oh, no!
- Girls, do you know John Connor?

207
00:26:56,885 --> 00:26:58,376
No.

208
00:27:00,556 --> 00:27:04,425
- Hey, do you know this guy?
- Nah, I don't know him.

209
00:27:11,025 --> 00:27:12,607
- John.
- Not now.

210
00:27:12,818 --> 00:27:15,652
Hey, there's this cop
scoping for you. Check it out.

211
00:27:19,116 --> 00:27:21,028
- He's right over there.
- Split, man.

212
00:27:21,243 --> 00:27:23,155
- Just go.
- Yeah.

213
00:27:28,417 --> 00:27:29,407
I saw that kid...

214
00:27:29,627 --> 00:27:30,743
Hey!

215
00:27:45,100 --> 00:27:46,807
Hey! You're not supposed to be in here!

216
00:28:04,995 --> 00:28:06,531
Hey!

217
00:28:12,670 --> 00:28:13,706
Get down.

218
00:29:24,867 --> 00:29:26,654
Mister, are you all right?

219
00:29:44,511 --> 00:29:45,547
Come on!

220
00:30:25,803 --> 00:30:27,135
Goddamn!

221
00:35:06,292 --> 00:35:08,659
Okay. Time out. Stop the bike.

222
00:35:08,878 --> 00:35:10,790
Time out. Come on, stop the bike.

223
00:35:24,644 --> 00:35:27,227
Holy shit.
Now, don't take this the wrong way.

224
00:35:27,438 --> 00:35:29,475
- But you are a Terminator, right?
- Yes.

225
00:35:29,690 --> 00:35:33,525
- Cyberdyne Systems, Model 101.
- No?

226
00:35:44,247 --> 00:35:48,332
Holy shit! You're really real.

227
00:35:50,753 --> 00:35:52,210
I mean...

228
00:35:54,882 --> 00:35:59,252
You're like a machine underneath,
right? But sort of alive outside?

229
00:35:59,470 --> 00:36:01,257
I'm a cybernetic organism:

230
00:36:01,472 --> 00:36:04,010
living tissue over metal endoskeleton.

231
00:36:18,906 --> 00:36:20,943
This is intense.

232
00:36:21,159 --> 00:36:23,867
Get a grip, John. Okay.

233
00:36:26,539 --> 00:36:28,531
You're not here to kill me.

234
00:36:28,749 --> 00:36:32,663
I figured that part out for myself.
So what's the deal?

235
00:36:32,879 --> 00:36:35,462
My mission is to protect you.

236
00:36:35,673 --> 00:36:38,165
Yeah? Who sent you?

237
00:36:39,468 --> 00:36:40,458
You did.

238
00:36:40,678 --> 00:36:42,010
35 years from now,

239
00:36:42,221 --> 00:36:45,589
you reprogrammed me to be
your protector here, in this time.

240
00:36:45,808 --> 00:36:48,551
Oh, this is deep.

241
00:36:50,646 --> 00:36:53,684
So this other guy,
he's a Terminator like you, right?

242
00:36:53,900 --> 00:36:57,359
Not like me. A T-1000, advanced prototype.

243
00:36:59,071 --> 00:37:03,486
- More advanced than you are?
- Yes. A mimetic poly-alloy.

244
00:37:04,410 --> 00:37:06,823
- What the hell does that mean?
- Liquid metal.

245
00:37:08,581 --> 00:37:09,697
Where are we going?

246
00:37:09,916 --> 00:37:13,117
We have to get out of the city
immediately and avoid the authorities.

247
00:37:13,920 --> 00:37:16,583
Listen, I got to stop by my house.
I want to pick up some stuff.

